Seg-SELL-C-œÉ does not outperform SELL-C-œÉ because the additional memory traÔ¨Éc, which
Seg-SELL-C-œÉ format requires, is larger than the reduced memory traÔ¨Éc for input vector by
column-wise segmentation. AMB (Level 1, 2) sets the block size in third level to 1. For
most of matrices, AMB (Level 1, 2) achieves speedups compared to SELL-C-œÉ format. We
Ô¨Ånd the elimination of needless chunks and compression of the column index to 16-bit integer
contribute the speedups of the performance of SpMV. AMB selects best block size in third
level, and shows further speedups. The result also shows the blocking optimization in third
level does not improve the performance when nz/row is small. This is because there are not
enough non-zero elements which have contiguous column indices in each row.
Figure 5 shows the ratio of the memory traÔ¨Éc compared to CSR format for each matrix
data. We evaluate the memory traÔ¨Éc of SELL-C-œÉ, BCCOO from yaSpMV and AMB format.
The result shows AMB format eÔ¨Äectively reduces the memory traÔ¨Éc if nz/row is larger. That is
why AMB format shows superior performance to other formats. On the other hand, in smaller
nz/row, the memory traÔ¨Éc of AMB format is not minimum in compared formats, and SELL-CœÉ is most eÔ¨Écient format in terms of memory traÔ¨Éc. For these matrices, AMB format requires
atomicAdd operations for output vector, which occupy large percentage in total memory traÔ¨Éc.
For most of matrix data, the format with minimum memory traÔ¨Éc shows best performance of
SpMV computation compared to other sparse formats.
